{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"62bb6181-ad8b-42b9-b045-6d694cdb63ad","content":"## 2. Configure NuGet.org (manual step)\n\nOn **nuget.org**, go to your package (or account) settings and register a **Trusted Publisher**:\n\n| Field | Value |\n|-------|-------|\n| Repository owner | `myorg` |\n| Repository name | `mylib` |\n| Workflow filename | `publish.yml` |\n| Environment | *(leave blank)* |\n\n## How it works\n\n- **No API key needed.** The `id-token: write` permission lets the runner request an OIDC token from GitHub.\n- NuGet.org validates the token against your trusted publisher registration (owner + repo + workflow).\n- `dotnet nuget push` automatically uses the OIDC token when no `--api-key` is provided and the source supports it.\n\n## To publish\n\n```bash\ngit tag v1.0.0\ngit push origin v1.0.0\n```\n\nThe workflow triggers on version tags and pushes the package via OIDC. Make sure your `.csproj` sets `<PackageId>`, `<Version>`, and `<Authors>` for a valid package.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"457324e3-82c8-43aa-a12a-9ff55eca1d6d","outputTokens":267,"requestId":"E3D2:6467:1CA96B8:20295C1:6A07BF75"},"id":"27d2654f-ef1e-4d3d-a14a-d7e04792c949","timestamp":"2026-05-16T00:51:08.946Z","parentId":"7b6e1ab5-caa4-4740-b982-12158e0de2e5"}
